      "also choosing all `b_i` to be distinct and outside of the above sets.\n\n#### Step 2.4: Specific Construction of `b`\n\n1. For each `i`, let `S_i = {b'_i | (a_i, b'_i) ∈ ε}`. Each `S_i` is finite because `ε` is finite. \n   - Therefore, `S = ⋃_i S_i` is finite. \n\n2. Since the set of all strings is infinite, there exists a string `s` not in `S`. \n   - Take `b_i = s` for all `i`. Then `(a_i, b_i) = (a_i, s)` is in `ε` only if `s ∈ S_i`. But `s ∉ S`, so `s ∉ S_i` for any `i`. \n   - Thus, no pair `(a_i, b_i)` is in `ε`.\n\nThis way, `a.zip b = [(a_1, s), ..., (a_n, s)]`, and we need to ensure that this list has no duplicates if `a` has duplicates. \n\nBut `[(a_1, s), ..., (a_n, s)]` is a list with duplicates if any `a_i = a_j`. \n\nTo avoid this, we can instead make `b_i` distinct for each `i`, not just avoiding `S_i`.\n\n#### Step 2.5: Correct Approach with Distinct `b_i`\n\n1. Consider the finite set `S = {b' | ∃ a_i, (a_i, b') ∈ ε}`. \n\n2. Since `S` is finite, and there are infinitely many strings, we can find infinitely many strings not in `S`. \n\n3. Therefore, we can choose `b_i` as follows: \n   - For each `i`, pick a unique `b_i ∉ S` (ensuring all `b_i` are distinct).\n\n   - This ensures that `(a_i, b_i) ∉ ε` because `b_i ∉ S`. \n\nBut to be more concrete, since `a.length = n`, we can pick `b_i` as strings `\"x_1\", \"x_2\", ..., \"x_n\"` (assuming `\"x_i\"` not in `S`), such that they are distinct and not in any `S_i`. \n\nBut to avoid complications, we can instead take `b_i = a_i ++ \"x\"`, and then adjust if this is in `ε`. \n\nHowever, this seems complex. \n\n#### Step 2.6: A Simpler Way to Find Distinct `b_i`\n\nA better approach:\n\n1. Note that there are infinitely many distinct strings, but only finitely many pairs in `ε`.\n\n2. Therefore, for any fixed `a_i`, there are only finitely many `b_i` such that `(a_i, b_i) ∈ ε`.\n\n3. We can choose `b_i` to be any string not in that finite set for the `i`-th element. \n\nBut we need all `b_i` distinct (`a.zip b` should have no duplicates).\n\nAn efficient way is to first collect all `b'` in `ε` as:\n`S = { b' | ∃ a', (a', b') ∈ ε }`.\n\nThen pick any set of `n = a.length` distinct strings not in `S`, say `s_1, s_2, ..., s_n`, and take `b = [s_1, s_2, ..., s_n]`.\n\nBut then we need to ensure that in `a.zip b`, all pairs are distinct. \n\nIf `a` itself is `[..., x, ..., x, ...]`, then `a.zip b` will have duplicates unless the corresponding `s_i` are also the same. \n\nBut if we instead require that all pairs `(a_i, b_i)` are not in `ε`, we don't need to worry about duplicates unless it's required.\n\nBut the problem requires `(a.zip b).Nodup`. \n\nThus, if we take `b` as above, `a.zip b` will have no duplicates **only if `a` itself has no duplicates and we ensure that `s_i` are distinct**. \n\nBut if `a` itself has duplicates, then `a.zip b` will have duplicates unless `b` also duplicates, e.g., if `a = [x, x]`, and `b = [s_1, s_2]`, then `a.zip b = [(x, s_1), (x, s_2)]` is already nodup because `s_1 ≠ s_2`.\n\nNo: it's always nodup because the second components `s_i` are distinct.\n\nThis is fine: if `b_i` are all distinct, then `a.zip b` can only have duplicate pairs if some `(a_i, b_i) = (a_j, b_j)` with `i ≠ j`, but then `b_i = b_j`, which cannot happen if all `b_i` are distinct.\n\nTherefore, the requirement that `a.zip b` is nodup is automatically satisfied if all `b_i` are distinct. \n\n#### Step 2.7: Final Approach\n\n1. Define `S = {b' | ∃ a', (a', b') ∈ ε}`.\n    - Since `ε` is finite, `S` is finite.\n    - Let `m = S.card`.\n\n2. The set of all strings not in `S` is nonempty and in fact infinite. \n    - We can pick `a.length` many distinct strings not in `S`, as follows:\n      - Let `k = a.length`, and let `t_i = \"s\" ++ (i + m + 1 : String)` for `i ∈ {0, ..., k - 1}`.\n      - These `t_i` are distinct and not in `S`, because `\"s\" ++ (i + m + 1 : String)` cannot be of the form of any element in `S` (as we are assuming `S` does not contain any `\"s\" ++ ...`, which is not necessarily true).\n\n    - A better choice is to note that the set of `t : String` such that `t ∉ S` is nonempty and in bijection with `(Sᶜ : Set String)`. \n\n    - Since we have `k` many positions in `a`, we can pick any `k` distinct strings not in `S`.\n\n3. To formalize this, we can use that `Sᶜ` is infinite and thus contain a subset of size `k`. \n\nHowever, Lean's `Finset` doesn't directly give us an element in the complement. \n\nAn easier way is to consider the list of all elements in `ε` (as pairs) and construct `b_i` to avoid their second components in a systematic way. \n\nAlternatively, we can use the fact that there exists at least one string not in `S`, and then generate other strings from that. \n\nBut to avoid too much complexity, perhaps we can do as follows:\n\n1. Take `n = a.length`.\n2. For each element of `a`, we need to find some `b'_i` not in `{b | (a_i, b) ∈ ε}`. \n   - This can be done by taking any `b'_i` not in the finite set `{b | (a_i, b) ∈ ε}`. For example, `b'_i` could be `(card {b | (a_i, b) ∈ ε} : ℕ) + 1` as a string, or `\"default\"` if `ε` does not contain `(a_i, \"default\")`.\n   - But this may cause `b'_i` and `b'_j` to coincide when `a_i ≠ a_j`.\n   - However, we can instead define `b` such that all `b_i` are distinct and not in `S`.\n\nBut perhaps the following approach works better:\n\n#### Step 2.8: Concrete Construction Using `List.replicate`\n\nWe can define `b` as the list of correct length, consisting of strings that are not in any pair in `ε`. \n\nBut we need `b_i` to be distinct. \n\nInstead:\n\n1. Take the `Finset` of all second components of `ε`: `S' = { b' | ∃ a', (a', b') ∈ ε }`.\n   - This is equivalent to `S` above.\n\n2. Find `n = a.length` distinct strings outside `S'`. \n\nThis is possible because there are infinitely many strings. \n\n   - For instance, take `n` distinct natural numbers greater than all lengths of strings in `S'`, and convert them to strings. \n   - Alternatively,